WEBVTT

00:00.496 --> 00:03.429
[ALARM RINGING]

00:04.256 --> 00:06.295
Is Owen asleep?

00:09.102 --> 00:12.037
Yep, coast is clear.

00:14.207 --> 00:16.355
See you in the morning.

00:17.534 --> 00:19.669
See you in the morning.

00:21.000 --> 00:27.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:34.227 --> 00:35.627
So I bought a ticket for Minneapolis.

00:35.662 --> 00:37.696
I'm heading out tonight.

00:37.731 --> 00:39.198
Really?

00:39.232 --> 00:42.434
We'll see what she has to say
face-to-face.

00:42.469 --> 00:44.933
Connor, you sure that you
don't want to...

00:45.071 --> 00:47.139
I don't know, just, uh,

00:47.207 --> 00:48.824
think about let... letting it go?

00:48.864 --> 00:50.926
I'm sorry, Dr. Charles.

00:51.200 --> 00:55.305
I love your daughter.
I'm not going to lose her.

00:55.705 --> 00:57.672
[ALARM BEEPS]

00:57.707 --> 00:59.342
Get it away from me!

00:59.367 --> 01:01.543
Dr. Choi, Dr. Manning!
You're going to 3.

01:01.577 --> 01:03.678
I got LeAnn Crawford, 22,

01:03.713 --> 01:06.076
found attached to her newborn
on the sidewalk

01:06.116 --> 01:07.382
in a pool of blood.

01:07.416 --> 01:09.017
Combative in the field.
I couldn't cut the cord.

01:09.051 --> 01:10.788
- Drugs?
- Wouldn't surprise me.

01:10.828 --> 01:13.632
- Get it away from me!
- Ma'am, this is your baby.

01:13.657 --> 01:15.429
Oh, no, it's a... it's a monster.

01:15.454 --> 01:18.235
She may be in withdrawal.
I need 4 milligrams of Versed, IV.

01:18.269 --> 01:19.498
- On it.
- Not until we cut the cord.

01:19.523 --> 01:20.701
Please get this thing away from me!

01:20.726 --> 01:23.052
Let's get her in restraints!
Ma'am, I need you to listen to me.

01:23.077 --> 01:24.671
Get it away!

01:24.696 --> 01:27.164
Whoa, she tore the cord!

01:27.275 --> 01:29.677
[BABY CRIES]

01:29.711 --> 01:31.744
All right, let's transfer on my count.

01:32.013 --> 01:35.416
Ready? One, two, three.

01:35.596 --> 01:37.263
Give her the Versed. She's bleeding out.

01:37.290 --> 01:38.657
We've got to deliver this placenta now.

01:38.692 --> 01:40.459
No, it's a... it's a monster!

01:40.494 --> 01:41.994
Kill... kill it.

01:42.029 --> 01:44.547
Baby's temp is 94. I need more blankets!

01:44.572 --> 01:46.265
- Versed's in!
- Let's start an IV.

01:46.299 --> 01:48.834
Get two units of O neg on the rapid
transfuser and start the MTP.

01:48.869 --> 01:50.069
Vitals at 86.

01:50.111 --> 01:52.112
Turn the O2 up to ten liters.

01:52.139 --> 01:53.806
I got the placenta.

01:53.840 --> 01:56.342
Heart rate's down. Pressure's stable.

01:56.376 --> 01:58.144
Baby's starting to pink up.

01:58.233 --> 02:00.801
Hey. Hey, listen to me.

02:00.831 --> 02:03.132
You just had a baby.

02:03.166 --> 02:06.035
That's your baby.

02:06.069 --> 02:07.736
Baby?

02:07.771 --> 02:09.872
[BABY CRIES]

02:09.906 --> 02:12.342
Call Child and Family Services.

02:12.376 --> 02:15.212
No way she's taking this baby home.

02:15.246 --> 02:18.048
Baby? Baby?

02:18.082 --> 02:21.051
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

02:21.085 --> 02:23.736
<i>♪</i>

02:23.783 --> 02:28.381
<font color="#0080ff">Synced & corrected by</font> kinglouisxx
<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

02:30.061 --> 02:32.195
- [DEVICE BEEPS]
- Okay.

02:32.230 --> 02:34.664
Temperature's back to 98.

02:34.699 --> 02:36.900
I'll be back to check on him
in a little bit.

02:36.934 --> 02:38.568
Poor thing.

02:38.603 --> 02:41.938
Let me know if anything changes.

02:41.973 --> 02:44.207
[SIGHS]

02:44.242 --> 02:46.109
Hey, how's the mom?

02:46.144 --> 02:48.044
Better, apparently,
after a little methadone.

02:48.079 --> 02:49.779
I'm gonna talk to her about detox.

02:49.814 --> 02:51.181
Tox screen showed heroin.

02:51.215 --> 02:52.682
Great. Odds are the baby's

02:52.717 --> 02:53.884
going to have the same result.

02:53.918 --> 02:56.720
Eh, never know.
Might be a high-stress user.

02:56.754 --> 02:58.622
Baby could be fine.

02:58.656 --> 03:00.590
Maybe.

03:00.625 --> 03:01.625
[KNOCKING]

03:01.659 --> 03:03.026
Ms. Crawford?

03:03.060 --> 03:04.427
I'm Dr. Charles. Uh...

03:04.462 --> 03:06.396
glad to see you're doing
a little better.

03:06.430 --> 03:09.633
Anything we can get you?
Something to drink?

03:09.667 --> 03:11.101
I just want to go.

03:11.135 --> 03:12.903
I don't blame you,
but we do need to make sure

03:12.937 --> 03:14.571
that you're stable first.

03:14.605 --> 03:18.542
So, you do understand that
the DCFS is on the way

03:18.576 --> 03:21.545
to arrange a custodian for your child?

03:21.579 --> 03:22.779
Yeah.

03:22.813 --> 03:24.179
Okay.

03:24.204 --> 03:26.685
I was looking at your tox
screen and I'm just curious.

03:26.710 --> 03:28.985
How long have you been using for?

03:29.020 --> 03:31.555
Roughly?

03:31.589 --> 03:34.658
The reason I ask is that we do
have a number of programs here

03:34.692 --> 03:37.227
at the hospital that are...
that are available to you.

03:37.261 --> 03:38.662
One particular, um...

03:38.696 --> 03:40.597
I-I said I-I just want to go.

03:40.631 --> 03:42.299
I understand that, but this
would be an opportunity...

03:42.333 --> 03:44.668
Dr. Charles,
can I talk to you for a second?

03:44.702 --> 03:47.671
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

03:47.705 --> 03:50.073
Yeah.

03:50.107 --> 03:54.077
Uh, get some rest. I'll, uh,
check in with you later.

03:54.111 --> 03:57.147
<i>♪</i>

03:57.181 --> 03:58.648
You're wasting your time.

03:58.683 --> 04:00.850
You do understand
that we have an obligation

04:00.885 --> 04:02.586
to try to get addicts into a program

04:02.620 --> 04:04.321
- before they leave the hospital?
- Yeah, but clearly,

04:04.355 --> 04:05.822
- she doesn't want our help.
- We don't know that.

04:05.856 --> 04:07.591
We almost never get through
on the first shot.

04:07.625 --> 04:09.292
She won't even talk to you, Dr. Charles.

04:09.327 --> 04:10.927
Ethan, somebody puts up
a wall like that...

04:10.962 --> 04:13.296
they're usually trying
to protect something.

04:13.331 --> 04:15.832
That's often worth chipping away at.

04:15.866 --> 04:19.668
<i>♪</i>

04:23.140 --> 04:25.408
Barry.

04:26.410 --> 04:28.545
Can you not see that I'm working?

04:28.579 --> 04:31.381
I'm just trying to get a closer look.

04:31.415 --> 04:35.552
Observing the charge nurse
in her natural habitat.

04:35.586 --> 04:37.153
Aren't the paramedics supposed to

04:37.188 --> 04:39.155
drop off their patients and leave?

04:39.190 --> 04:41.524
Not paramedics with an agenda.

04:41.559 --> 04:43.560
Mm.

04:43.594 --> 04:45.562
Have dinner with me tonight.

04:45.596 --> 04:48.198
My answer's the same
as it was last time:

04:48.232 --> 04:49.899
no.

04:49.934 --> 04:51.801
Why not?

04:51.836 --> 04:53.236
We went out for drinks.

04:53.271 --> 04:54.371
Right, drinks.

04:54.405 --> 04:55.872
That's not a date.

04:55.906 --> 04:57.474
Having dinner is dating,

04:57.508 --> 05:00.043
and we are not having dinner.

05:00.077 --> 05:01.411
Well, not yet.

05:01.445 --> 05:05.015
It's not even lunchtime.

05:05.049 --> 05:06.783
[TAPS DESK]

05:08.452 --> 05:11.488
Hey, Miss Dempsey. Mr. Goodwin.

05:11.522 --> 05:12.656
- Dr. Halstead.
- Haven't seen you in a while.

05:12.690 --> 05:14.257
- What's going on?
- Still no cure

05:14.292 --> 05:16.359
for supranuclear palsy, as you can see.

05:16.394 --> 05:18.094
But we do therapy three times a week

05:18.129 --> 05:20.063
and try to get around the block
every night after dinner.

05:20.097 --> 05:21.665
That's good.

05:21.699 --> 05:24.267
Let's get you onto the bed here.

05:24.302 --> 05:25.869
Oh. [COUGHS]

05:25.903 --> 05:27.404
I see they keep making these things

05:27.438 --> 05:28.772
higher and higher.

05:28.806 --> 05:30.507
Yeah, it's completely unacceptable.

05:30.541 --> 05:32.208
I'll look into it immediately.

05:32.243 --> 05:33.677
[LAUGHS]

05:33.711 --> 05:34.878
[COUGHS]

05:34.912 --> 05:36.913
How long have you had that cough?

05:36.947 --> 05:39.449
[SIGHS] A few days now.

05:39.483 --> 05:41.518
- [DEVICE BEEPS]
- Temp's 103.

05:41.552 --> 05:43.687
Has the palsy been making it
harder to swallow?

05:43.721 --> 05:46.690
Uh, yeah, in the last couple of months.

05:46.724 --> 05:48.692
Bert keeps making me smoothies,

05:48.726 --> 05:52.128
but I sneak in a granola bar
every now and then.

05:52.163 --> 05:53.763
Lean forward for me, would you?

05:53.798 --> 05:55.265
Sure.

06:02.173 --> 06:03.473
Yeah, you're pretty clogged up.

06:03.507 --> 06:04.774
Wouldn't surprise me if

06:04.809 --> 06:06.042
something went down the wrong tube

06:06.077 --> 06:07.138
and turned into a pneumonia.

06:07.163 --> 06:08.855
Well, you can treat that, can't you?

06:08.880 --> 06:11.314
Yes. I'm gonna start
you on some antibiotics

06:11.349 --> 06:12.382
while we wait for the culture results,

06:12.416 --> 06:13.783
but for right now,

06:13.818 --> 06:14.818
you do nothing,

06:14.852 --> 06:15.819
and I'll be back soon.

06:15.853 --> 06:17.053
I can do that.

06:17.088 --> 06:18.855
Good.

06:22.927 --> 06:24.828
Dr. Halstead?

06:24.862 --> 06:27.564
I know she has a degenerative disease,

06:27.598 --> 06:30.066
and that I won't have her
forever, but, uh,

06:30.101 --> 06:32.569
her mind's all there.

06:32.603 --> 06:35.338
I want to be able to take her home.

06:35.373 --> 06:38.808
I promise I'm gonna do everything I can.

06:38.843 --> 06:40.810
Thank you.

06:40.845 --> 06:42.412
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

06:42.446 --> 06:45.483
- Hey, dinner tonight?
- Can't.

06:45.516 --> 06:47.951
Going to watch Noah's hockey game.

06:47.985 --> 06:50.153
I know that stuff's
not a big deal to you,

06:50.187 --> 06:51.321
but it's important to me.

06:51.355 --> 06:52.589
"That stuff"? You mean

06:52.623 --> 06:54.090
adult rec league sports?

06:54.125 --> 06:55.658
I mean family.

06:55.693 --> 06:57.627
Why do you think family's
not a big deal to me?

06:57.661 --> 07:00.296
I don't know. You never talk about them.

07:00.331 --> 07:02.799
There's nothing to talk about.

07:02.833 --> 07:04.834
Okay.

07:04.869 --> 07:06.269
Hey, Ava.

07:06.303 --> 07:08.338
Can you cover for me tomorrow?

07:08.372 --> 07:09.706
Sure. Are you getting sick?

07:09.740 --> 07:11.341
No, I'm headed to Minneapolis.

07:11.375 --> 07:14.778
That sounds even worse.
Why are you going there?

07:14.812 --> 07:17.280
Oh, is that where Robin moved to?

07:17.314 --> 07:18.448
Yeah, it is.

07:18.482 --> 07:19.649
So, this is what,

07:19.683 --> 07:21.451
a misguided attempt to win her back?

07:21.485 --> 07:23.453
- Forget I asked.
- No, I'm happy to do it,

07:23.487 --> 07:24.788
mostly because I find your gift

07:24.822 --> 07:26.790
for self-flagellation fascinating.

07:26.824 --> 07:28.391
What is that supposed to mean?

07:28.426 --> 07:29.793
Just that, from what
I gather, this sounds like

07:29.827 --> 07:30.794
a fool's errand.

07:30.828 --> 07:33.396
CT's own Dr. Phil? Thank you.

07:33.431 --> 07:34.631
Dr. who?

07:34.665 --> 07:36.733
Dr. Rhodes, CFD just called.

07:36.767 --> 07:38.668
They've got a man trapped
in a collapsed building

07:38.702 --> 07:40.303
and need a surgeon.
You're on trauma today?

07:40.337 --> 07:41.638
- I am.
- Good.

07:41.672 --> 07:43.173
Ambo's waiting
to take you there right now,

07:43.207 --> 07:44.541
and take Dr. Bekker, too.

07:44.575 --> 07:46.142
You could use a second pair of hands.

07:46.177 --> 07:47.377
She is CT. How about

07:47.411 --> 07:48.578
one of the other trauma surgeons?

07:48.612 --> 07:49.813
I'm already losing you.

07:49.847 --> 07:51.381
I can't afford to lose another.

07:51.415 --> 07:53.483
I'll let Dr. Latham know where you are.

07:53.517 --> 07:55.653
Let's move it.

07:56.411 --> 07:58.655
- [KNOCKS]
- You wanted to see me?

07:58.689 --> 08:01.224
Yeah, uh, what's the status

08:01.258 --> 08:03.393
on Dr. Reese's probation?

08:03.427 --> 08:05.094
Well, she's been doing

08:05.129 --> 08:06.763
daily individualized therapy

08:06.797 --> 08:08.498
and a course in hospital safety,

08:08.532 --> 08:10.667
so she should be in good shape
to start back up.

08:10.701 --> 08:12.735
Uh, good. I'd like you to give me

08:12.770 --> 08:15.872
a detailed progress report
once she returns to work.

08:15.906 --> 08:18.074
Well, actually, I'm not going
to be supervising her anymore.

08:18.108 --> 08:20.343
She's going to be working
under Dr. Chapman.

08:20.377 --> 08:21.611
Why?

08:21.645 --> 08:23.012
Under my supervision, Dr. Reese

08:23.047 --> 08:25.181
assaulted a patient with pepper spray.

08:25.216 --> 08:27.684
You know, and... I don't know.
My clinical approach

08:27.718 --> 08:29.619
might have had something
to do with it, so...

08:29.653 --> 08:31.254
I just think for now,

08:31.288 --> 08:33.356
Dr. Chapman might be a better fit.

08:33.390 --> 08:35.958
Okay. Whatever you think is best.

08:35.993 --> 08:37.527
Okay.

08:37.561 --> 08:39.028
Uh, Sharon, I heard that...

08:39.063 --> 08:40.530
that Bert's back in the hospital today.

08:40.563 --> 08:44.200
Yeah, I heard that, too.

08:44.235 --> 08:48.238
<i>♪</i>

08:48.272 --> 08:50.540
[BABY CRYING]

08:50.574 --> 08:52.575
Dr. Manning.

08:52.610 --> 08:54.077
- What's going on?
- He's inconsolable.

08:54.111 --> 08:56.279
I've tried rocking him, swaddling him,

08:56.313 --> 08:57.714
singing. Nothing I do calms him down.

08:57.748 --> 08:59.282
[SOFTLY] Oh, hi.

08:59.316 --> 09:00.717
Heart rate's in the 190s.

09:00.751 --> 09:02.452
O2 sats have been dropping.

09:02.486 --> 09:03.953
Has he been feeding?

09:03.988 --> 09:05.054
No, nothing.

09:05.089 --> 09:07.724
Is it possible he's still
in shock from the cold?

09:07.758 --> 09:09.993
I don't think so.

09:10.027 --> 09:11.394
I'll go see if his labs are back.

09:11.428 --> 09:13.229
That won't be necessary.

09:13.264 --> 09:14.898
He's addicted to heroin.

09:14.932 --> 09:15.798
[BABY CRIES]

09:15.833 --> 09:17.400
He's going through withdrawal.

09:17.434 --> 09:19.335
[BABY CRIES]

09:19.901 --> 09:21.789
Shh.

09:25.182 --> 09:26.681
I heard about the baby.

09:26.716 --> 09:28.548
Neonatal abstinence syndrome.

09:28.573 --> 09:30.369
That's a... that's a rough road.

09:30.393 --> 09:32.160
Yeah, I'm giving him fluids, Ativan,

09:32.194 --> 09:33.892
and aspiration precautions,

09:33.917 --> 09:36.097
but his numbers aren't
getting any better.

09:36.132 --> 09:37.599
How's the mom?

09:37.633 --> 09:39.601
Just wants to get out
and get her next fix.

09:39.635 --> 09:40.635
Why?

09:40.669 --> 09:42.871
Studies show that babies
who are not thriving

09:42.905 --> 09:44.472
actually do significantly better

09:44.507 --> 09:45.640
when they have physical contact

09:45.674 --> 09:46.841
with their biological mothers.

09:46.892 --> 09:48.781
- So?
- So I think we should

09:48.806 --> 09:50.478
have LeAnn hold him for a little bit.

09:50.513 --> 09:51.859
You can't be serious.
She tried to kill him.

09:51.884 --> 09:53.782
She would be supervised.

09:53.816 --> 09:55.483
Even hearing the mother's heartbeat

09:55.518 --> 09:57.318
can lower cortisol levels and stress.

09:57.353 --> 09:58.476
LeAnn had nine months

09:58.501 --> 10:00.221
to do right by her baby.
She lost that chance.

10:00.256 --> 10:02.342
- Dr. Charles...
- Well, I appreciate

10:02.367 --> 10:03.958
your concern for your...
for your patient,

10:03.993 --> 10:06.127
Dr. Manning, but I'm also
concerned for mine,

10:06.162 --> 10:07.529
and here's the problem.

10:07.563 --> 10:09.798
That baby's going home
with somebody else.

10:09.832 --> 10:13.234
We let LeAnn bond with him,
and then just rip him away?

10:13.269 --> 10:16.922
Any chance we have of helping
her... pretty much gone for good.

10:16.969 --> 10:19.671
Dr. Charles, we're talking
about an infant's life.

10:19.705 --> 10:21.606
I'm aware of that, but I just think that

10:21.641 --> 10:23.608
we should take a beat
and look at all sides of this.

10:23.643 --> 10:25.243
Excuse me, Dr. Manning.

10:25.278 --> 10:26.912
DCFS is on their way.

10:26.946 --> 10:28.346
They've got some foster parents

10:28.381 --> 10:29.581
that might be interested

10:29.615 --> 10:31.416
in caring for your patient.

10:31.450 --> 10:32.584
Good. Um, just have them

10:32.618 --> 10:33.818
give me a little bit of time.

10:33.853 --> 10:35.687
Okay? Um, the baby's not stable yet.

10:35.721 --> 10:39.090
- I'll do my best.
- Thank you.

10:39.125 --> 10:41.526
Oh, hey, Sharon.

10:41.561 --> 10:43.495
Hello, Bert.

10:43.529 --> 10:45.664
Uh, how's Miss Dempsey doing?

10:45.698 --> 10:47.766
Well, hopefully,
we'll be out of here soon.

10:47.800 --> 10:49.534
Dr. Halstead's on top of it.

10:49.569 --> 10:51.269
Well, that's good.

10:51.304 --> 10:52.804
And how are you doing?

10:52.838 --> 10:54.272
Me? I'm, you know, the same:

10:54.307 --> 10:57.275
hanging in there,
trying to help as best I can.

10:57.310 --> 10:59.644
Well, I'm sure it isn't easy.

10:59.679 --> 11:01.446
No, it isn't.

11:01.480 --> 11:04.182
Watching her get
a little worse every day

11:04.217 --> 11:05.784
and struggling with the things

11:05.818 --> 11:10.055
that were easy
just a few weeks ago and...

11:10.089 --> 11:11.356
Ah.

11:11.390 --> 11:14.192
Anyhow, I... I should get back.

11:14.227 --> 11:16.494
Yeah.

11:18.764 --> 11:20.332
Once you return to work,

11:20.366 --> 11:21.733
we'll round twice a day,

11:21.767 --> 11:23.301
do a chart review every morning,

11:23.336 --> 11:26.238
and you'll observe
group therapy every afternoon.

11:26.272 --> 11:28.340
By "observe," do you mean
I will be sitting in?

11:28.374 --> 11:30.642
No, we have a one-way mirror.

11:30.676 --> 11:33.979
I don't believe in using
house staff as cheap labor.

11:34.013 --> 11:35.413
You first.

11:35.448 --> 11:37.916
Residency is a time to watch

11:37.950 --> 11:40.051
and absorb.

11:40.086 --> 11:41.987
Um, okay.

11:42.021 --> 11:43.655
Uh, though, speaking about therapy,

11:43.689 --> 11:45.991
I've been reading up on
Erikson's theories

11:46.025 --> 11:48.994
uh, for strategic interaction,
and it's an interesting take,

11:49.028 --> 11:50.996
focusing on a patient's, uh,
personal strengths,

11:51.030 --> 11:52.597
rather than their pathologies.

11:52.632 --> 11:54.499
Yes, interactional therapy
is interesting, but

11:54.533 --> 11:56.534
you should spend the rest
of your suspension

11:56.569 --> 11:58.670
learning these.

11:58.704 --> 12:00.171
What are they?

12:00.206 --> 12:01.606
Treatment algorithms

12:01.641 --> 12:03.908
for the seven most common
conditions we see.

12:03.943 --> 12:05.777
But these are flow charts.

12:05.811 --> 12:07.612
How do you individualize the therapy?

12:07.647 --> 12:09.080
Step three.

12:09.115 --> 12:11.283
Is the patient responding to medication?

12:11.317 --> 12:14.052
Yes, no.

12:14.086 --> 12:16.354
Thursday afternoons, we do journal club.

12:16.389 --> 12:19.157
You're welcome to listen in.

12:20.826 --> 12:22.894
- What happened?
- Building's condemned.

12:22.928 --> 12:24.229
Supposed to be empty,

12:24.263 --> 12:25.964
but we thought we heard somebody inside.

12:25.998 --> 12:27.532
Turned out to be a squatter.
Guy's name is Gary.

12:27.566 --> 12:28.767
He's got a big chunk of concrete

12:28.801 --> 12:30.368
compressing his left leg

12:30.403 --> 12:32.203
and a piece of rebar
straight up through his groin.

12:32.238 --> 12:33.872
We got pressure on it,
but he's bleeding pretty bad.

12:33.906 --> 12:35.106
If we stop the bleed,
can we get him out?

12:35.141 --> 12:37.208
- Hard to say.
- Hey, Lieutenant!

12:37.243 --> 12:39.711
- Yeah?
- Uh, the concrete's a bear.

12:39.745 --> 12:41.579
We can't use the bags on it,

12:41.614 --> 12:42.881
but we might be able to

12:42.915 --> 12:45.717
break it up with the air chisel.

12:45.751 --> 12:47.319
Be careful. We haven't been able to

12:47.353 --> 12:50.655
clear a path yet, so we're
gonna have to sneak through.

12:50.690 --> 12:53.391
- Watch your heads.
- Yeah.

12:53.426 --> 12:55.126
Ah, here we go, Gary.

12:55.161 --> 12:56.728
We got Dr. Rhodes

12:56.762 --> 12:59.230
and Dr. Bekker.

12:59.265 --> 13:00.632
Now, Gary,

13:00.666 --> 13:03.835
we're gonna take
good care of you, all right?

13:03.869 --> 13:07.939
All right. Hey, you're okay.

13:07.973 --> 13:09.140
All right, draw up
another round of labs,

13:09.175 --> 13:11.242
- and hang a gram of vanco.
- Yep.

13:11.277 --> 13:13.144
Hey, Ms. Dempsey.

13:13.179 --> 13:16.648
The antibiotics aren't
working, are they?

13:16.682 --> 13:18.450
No, they're not,

13:18.484 --> 13:20.185
and it's possible the bacteria

13:20.219 --> 13:23.321
has spread from your lungs
into your blood.

13:23.356 --> 13:25.657
Sepsis.

13:25.691 --> 13:27.659
I've been reading.

13:27.693 --> 13:29.260
Yes.

13:29.295 --> 13:31.863
Now, I'm hoping this
new antibiotic we're starting

13:31.897 --> 13:33.932
will turn things around,

13:33.966 --> 13:36.267
but, as you know, the supranuclear palsy

13:36.302 --> 13:37.936
makes your immune system less effective,

13:37.970 --> 13:39.871
so there's also a chance
before we get there

13:39.905 --> 13:42.607
your lungs will start to give out.

13:42.641 --> 13:44.509
Now, if it comes to that,

13:44.543 --> 13:47.112
I am gonna have to intubate you.

13:47.146 --> 13:49.214
And put me on a ventilator?

13:49.248 --> 13:50.648
Yes.

13:50.683 --> 13:51.950
But hopefully, it's only temporary,

13:51.984 --> 13:53.618
until we can clear the infection.

13:53.652 --> 13:55.653
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

13:55.688 --> 13:57.455
Okay?

13:57.490 --> 13:59.324
<i>♪</i>

13:59.358 --> 14:00.792
Hang in there.

14:00.826 --> 14:03.628
I'll be back to check on you
in a few minutes.

14:03.662 --> 14:05.296
Dr. Halstead?

14:05.331 --> 14:07.799
<i>♪</i>

14:07.833 --> 14:11.169
I don't want that ventilator.

14:11.203 --> 14:13.538
I understand this sounds daunting,

14:13.572 --> 14:15.173
but like I said, if it comes to that,

14:15.207 --> 14:17.642
we may very well be able
to get you off it again soon.

14:17.676 --> 14:19.878
Or you may not.

14:19.912 --> 14:22.247
I know how this all ends.

14:22.281 --> 14:24.182
Lyla,

14:24.216 --> 14:26.718
if your lungs fail and I don't intubate,

14:26.752 --> 14:28.553
you'll die.

14:28.587 --> 14:30.221
<i>♪</i>

14:30.256 --> 14:32.724
I know.

14:32.758 --> 14:35.827
<i>♪</i>

14:35.861 --> 14:37.662
Okay.

14:37.696 --> 14:42.734
<i>♪</i>

14:42.768 --> 14:44.669
Ms. Crawford?

14:44.703 --> 14:46.371
I told you, I don't want to talk.

14:46.405 --> 14:48.373
Uh, I'm not here to discuss detox.

14:48.407 --> 14:51.363
I want to talk to you about your baby.

14:51.388 --> 14:52.544
What about it?

14:52.578 --> 14:54.777
He's a boy,

14:54.947 --> 14:57.137
and he's withdrawing from heroin.

14:57.283 --> 15:00.098
He's, um, not eating, not sleeping.

15:00.270 --> 15:04.722
Breathing and heartbeat aren't
quite as regular as we'd like.

15:04.757 --> 15:06.858
So give him some medicine.

15:06.892 --> 15:08.693
Well, we have been, but...

15:08.727 --> 15:11.262
it is not quite that simple.

15:11.297 --> 15:13.631
Okay.

15:13.666 --> 15:15.900
Um...

15:18.337 --> 15:19.804
So?

15:19.839 --> 15:21.606
LeAnn, adults have years

15:21.640 --> 15:23.475
to develop the coping mechanisms

15:23.509 --> 15:27.078
that helps us get through
life's trouble spots.

15:27.112 --> 15:29.047
Uh, a newborn doesn't have any.

15:29.081 --> 15:31.149
You know, for him, his mother

15:31.183 --> 15:32.817
is the only thing in the world

15:32.852 --> 15:34.652
that makes him feel safe.

15:34.687 --> 15:36.054
Being held by her,

15:36.088 --> 15:39.057
you know, feeling her skin...

15:39.091 --> 15:41.759
You want me to hold him?

15:41.794 --> 15:43.428
Well, it might be

15:43.462 --> 15:44.896
the best medicine we've got.

15:44.930 --> 15:49.334
<i>♪</i>

15:49.368 --> 15:50.969
I-I-I don't...

15:51.003 --> 15:53.071
I don't know how to hold a baby.

15:53.105 --> 15:54.239
Well, we can show you.

15:54.273 --> 15:57.141
We can teach you how to do that.

15:57.176 --> 15:58.226
But...

15:58.251 --> 16:01.876
this baby's sick 'cause of me, right?

16:02.481 --> 16:04.949
There's... there's no way
that more of me

16:04.984 --> 16:07.318
is gonna help it.

16:07.353 --> 16:09.187
Well...

16:09.221 --> 16:11.256
[WHISPERED] I said no.

16:11.290 --> 16:13.124
<i>♪</i>

16:13.158 --> 16:15.693
Please leave me alone.

16:15.728 --> 16:22.967
<i>♪</i>

16:27.973 --> 16:30.775
Ms. Dempsey?

16:30.809 --> 16:33.111
You wanted to see me?

16:33.145 --> 16:35.613
What can I do for you?

16:35.648 --> 16:39.317
I'm sure I'm the last person
you want to talk to.

16:39.351 --> 16:40.652
I know Bert

16:40.686 --> 16:42.787
didn't do right by you,

16:42.821 --> 16:44.722
but he's a good man.

16:44.757 --> 16:46.724
He shouldn't be alone.

16:46.759 --> 16:51.462
Well, he was fortunate
to have found you.

16:51.497 --> 16:53.965
Thank you.

16:53.999 --> 16:58.236
But he won't have me for long.

16:58.270 --> 17:02.473
I signed a do-not-resuscitate order.

17:02.508 --> 17:06.477
I see.

17:06.512 --> 17:09.981
So when my time does come,

17:10.015 --> 17:12.383
would you look after him?

17:12.417 --> 17:14.819
You don't have to answer now. Just...

17:14.853 --> 17:17.989
please think about it.

17:18.022 --> 17:25.229
<i>♪</i>

17:28.534 --> 17:31.102
Let's see what we got here, all right?

17:31.136 --> 17:33.171
[FLESH SQUELCHING]

17:33.205 --> 17:36.507
Wait, hold pressure, hold pressure.

17:36.542 --> 17:39.377
- All right.
- There.

17:39.411 --> 17:43.348
- Yep.
- Move your hands.

17:43.382 --> 17:45.016
Just a bit.

17:45.050 --> 17:46.517
Can you see it?

17:46.552 --> 17:48.019
<i>♪</i>

17:48.053 --> 17:49.854
No, can't clamp the artery.

17:49.888 --> 17:51.522
Rebar's in the way.

17:51.557 --> 17:54.092
Herrmann, any chance
of getting him out of here?

17:54.126 --> 17:55.627
We're gonna try the air chisels,

17:55.661 --> 17:57.895
but it don't look good.

17:57.930 --> 18:00.898
<i>♪</i>

18:00.933 --> 18:02.700
All right, we're gonna
have to do a REBOA.

18:02.735 --> 18:03.801
What?

18:03.836 --> 18:05.036
Gary?

18:05.070 --> 18:06.771
An ER-REBOA is a catheter

18:06.805 --> 18:09.207
with a balloon at the tip that
I can thread into your aorta.

18:09.241 --> 18:11.943
Once I inflate the balloon,

18:11.977 --> 18:13.578
it'll keep you from bleeding.

18:13.612 --> 18:15.480
Okay.

18:15.514 --> 18:16.748
One moment.

18:16.782 --> 18:18.249
- Ready.
- Keep pressure there.

18:18.283 --> 18:20.752
Got it. Yep, hang on.

18:20.786 --> 18:22.787
Watch it. Hang on, bud.

18:22.821 --> 18:25.056
Connor, we can't do that.

18:25.090 --> 18:26.591
Once you inflate the balloon,

18:26.625 --> 18:28.059
we'll only have 30 minutes
to get him out of here.

18:28.093 --> 18:29.927
He's lost too much blood already.

18:29.954 --> 18:32.397
It's gonna take a lot of
movement to get him out of here,

18:32.431 --> 18:34.098
and we won't be able
to maintain pressure.

18:34.133 --> 18:35.466
So you're going to risk

18:35.501 --> 18:37.001
prolonged loss of circulation instead?

18:37.036 --> 18:38.936
I realize it can necessitate amputation,

18:38.971 --> 18:40.738
but I promise you,

18:40.773 --> 18:42.106
if we don't place a REBOA,

18:42.141 --> 18:43.808
he's going to bleed out
right in front of us.

18:43.842 --> 18:45.076
Hey.

18:45.110 --> 18:46.844
- Yeah?
- Hey, what's going on?

18:46.879 --> 18:48.613
Nothing, Gary.

18:48.647 --> 18:52.293
We're gonna get you out of here
as fast as we can.

18:52.484 --> 18:53.751
Okay.

18:53.894 --> 18:55.586
Okay.

18:55.611 --> 18:58.579
<i>♪</i>

18:58.624 --> 19:00.925
Easy.

19:00.959 --> 19:03.261
<i>♪</i>

19:03.295 --> 19:06.369
Easy. Just breathe, buddy.

19:07.066 --> 19:08.939
Hang in there.

19:09.369 --> 19:11.637
All right, here we go.

19:11.970 --> 19:17.241
<i>♪</i>

19:19.764 --> 19:20.811
[KNOCKING]

19:20.836 --> 19:22.597
Come in.

19:24.783 --> 19:26.483
Dr. Reese.

19:26.651 --> 19:29.611
How'd it go with Dr. Chapman?

19:29.921 --> 19:31.588
Uh, it was fine.

19:31.623 --> 19:32.823
She's fine.

19:32.962 --> 19:34.501
Good.

19:35.095 --> 19:37.681
Is there an issue?

19:39.560 --> 19:42.275
I prefer to come back to your service.

19:42.634 --> 19:45.502
I understand, really, I do,

19:45.537 --> 19:48.135
but I-I think it's very
important that you explore

19:48.323 --> 19:50.941
a different clinical approach.

19:50.975 --> 19:53.677
Yeah, well, Dr. Charles,
I'm not an idiot.

19:53.712 --> 19:58.115
Um, I know you think my anxiety,

19:58.281 --> 19:59.849
my PTSD, if you will,

19:59.882 --> 20:02.397
stems directly from your being shot,

20:02.421 --> 20:03.788
that our working together is

20:03.823 --> 20:05.896
negatively affecting my mental health...

20:06.114 --> 20:07.892
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

20:07.927 --> 20:09.394
But...

20:09.428 --> 20:11.462
first of all, um,

20:11.552 --> 20:15.676
these are my issues,
and I'm working on them,

20:16.168 --> 20:18.168
and second of all,

20:18.370 --> 20:21.906
you chose to bring me into psychiatry...

20:21.941 --> 20:23.575
<i>♪</i>

20:23.609 --> 20:25.977
So I'm not about to let you pawn me off

20:26.011 --> 20:27.745
onto that Dr. Chapman...

20:27.780 --> 20:29.080
<i>♪</i>

20:29.114 --> 20:32.217
When you're the psychiatrist
I want to be.

20:32.251 --> 20:36.588
<i>♪</i>

20:36.622 --> 20:39.724
Um... I mean, I-I almost lost you once.

20:39.758 --> 20:42.894
I-I don't want to lose you again.

20:42.928 --> 20:44.495
<i>♪</i>

20:44.530 --> 20:47.398
Oh. I...

20:47.433 --> 20:49.500
I very much appreciate

20:49.535 --> 20:50.902
what you're saying,

20:50.936 --> 20:52.503
but as a... as a clinician,

20:52.538 --> 20:53.938
- and as a...
- Dr. Charles...

20:53.973 --> 20:57.842
And as a teacher,
I just think that this is

20:57.877 --> 21:01.279
the best course of action
that we stick with Dr. Chapman.

21:01.313 --> 21:08.586
<i>♪</i>

21:09.421 --> 21:10.722
Bert, stop.

21:10.756 --> 21:12.757
Sweetheart, this isn't right. No.

21:12.791 --> 21:14.959
Mr. Goodwin, it's not up to me.

21:14.994 --> 21:16.628
Bert, please...

21:16.662 --> 21:20.398
How can you not do anything?

21:21.300 --> 21:23.034
I explained all her options.

21:23.068 --> 21:24.435
But you're her doctor.

21:24.470 --> 21:25.703
Tell her what's best.

21:25.738 --> 21:26.771
She made her wishes very clear.

21:26.805 --> 21:28.573
There's nothing else I can do.

21:28.607 --> 21:30.742
So you're just going to
stand around and let her die?

21:30.776 --> 21:32.143
What the hell kind of hospital is this?

21:32.177 --> 21:34.412
- Bert, Bert...
- Bert.

21:34.446 --> 21:37.315
Bert.

21:37.349 --> 21:38.816
She needs another doctor,

21:38.851 --> 21:40.652
one who will do something
if she gets worse.

21:40.686 --> 21:42.387
Bert, this is her choice.

21:42.421 --> 21:43.755
She's got a fever.

21:43.789 --> 21:45.323
She doesn't know what she wants.

21:45.357 --> 21:46.991
This is hard, I know,

21:47.026 --> 21:48.459
but Dr. Halstead

21:48.494 --> 21:50.495
is doing everything he can

21:50.529 --> 21:52.830
within the scope of Lyla's wishes.

21:52.865 --> 21:55.433
The best thing you can do right now

21:55.467 --> 21:57.335
is go back in that room

21:57.369 --> 22:00.405
and be with her.

22:07.479 --> 22:10.415
How are you feeling?

22:10.449 --> 22:12.083
Fine.

22:17.723 --> 22:21.359
You don't think I should
go see my baby, do you?

22:21.393 --> 22:24.128
That's up to you.

22:25.564 --> 22:28.800
They say he's sick.

22:31.570 --> 22:34.706
Yeah, he is.

22:34.740 --> 22:37.875
I never planned on getting pregnant.

22:37.910 --> 22:40.511
You know?

22:43.248 --> 22:45.984
Whatever.

22:47.419 --> 22:50.688
You think I'm terrible.

22:50.723 --> 22:52.056
I just wish things had

22:52.091 --> 22:55.593
worked out differently
for you and your baby.

22:58.897 --> 23:01.799
Yeah.

23:01.834 --> 23:03.401
But I guess where you're from,

23:03.435 --> 23:06.738
things work out great for everybody.

23:06.772 --> 23:10.241
Why would you understand?

23:10.275 --> 23:13.711
Actually, I understand
a lot better than you think.

23:18.117 --> 23:19.417
- [KNOCKS]
- Oh.

23:19.451 --> 23:21.252
Getting hungry yet?

23:21.286 --> 23:25.056
I know you think
this is charming, but it's not.

23:25.090 --> 23:27.425
Hey, you remember our first date?

23:27.459 --> 23:29.594
Mm-hmm. Mexican food...

23:29.628 --> 23:31.896
- at the mall.
- No, I mean afterwards.

23:31.930 --> 23:34.499
We were throwing pennies into the pond

23:34.533 --> 23:36.167
where people made wishes.

23:36.201 --> 23:37.835
You know what mine was?

23:37.870 --> 23:39.704
A second date with the pretty woman

23:39.738 --> 23:40.772
sitting next to me.

23:40.806 --> 23:43.408
Hm. That's a sweet story.

23:43.442 --> 23:45.676
Too bad it ends
with you cheating on her.

23:45.711 --> 23:49.047
- I've changed, Maggie.
- So you say.

23:49.081 --> 23:52.984
But this time, I'm smart enough
to draw the line.

23:53.986 --> 23:57.188
- Maggie, just...
- Barry...

23:57.222 --> 23:58.890
[SIGHS]

23:58.924 --> 24:01.092
Okay.

24:08.600 --> 24:11.869
[MACHINES WHIRRING]

24:13.005 --> 24:15.473
[DEBRIS CRACKING AND FALLING]

24:15.507 --> 24:18.776
[MEN GRUNTING]

24:21.180 --> 24:22.647
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

24:22.681 --> 24:24.248
We're good. Keep going.

24:24.283 --> 24:26.451
This place is unstable.
Another shift like that,

24:26.485 --> 24:28.719
and the whole thing's
going to come down, Rhodes.

24:28.754 --> 24:30.154
Guys, you gotta do something.

24:30.189 --> 24:31.823
We could try coming from another angle,

24:31.857 --> 24:33.558
but it'll take 20 minutes.

24:33.592 --> 24:35.927
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

24:35.961 --> 24:37.728
His leg's already cold.

24:37.763 --> 24:38.996
All it's doing now is preventing us

24:39.031 --> 24:40.431
from getting him to hospital.

24:40.466 --> 24:41.833
<i>♪</i>

24:41.867 --> 24:43.601
Yeah.

24:43.635 --> 24:46.571
<i>♪</i>

24:46.605 --> 24:48.439
Gary...

24:48.474 --> 24:50.441
listen to me.

24:50.476 --> 24:52.009
Your leg is trapped

24:52.044 --> 24:53.845
and we need to get you out of here.

24:53.879 --> 24:55.513
I'm afraid that the only way to do that

24:55.547 --> 24:57.648
is to amputate.

24:57.683 --> 25:00.118
What? No.

25:00.152 --> 25:01.152
Gary, I'm very sorry,

25:01.186 --> 25:03.855
but your leg has gone
without blood for too long.

25:03.889 --> 25:05.523
Is that 'cause of that thing
you put in me?

25:05.557 --> 25:06.757
That balloon?

25:06.792 --> 25:08.192
We had to do that so you wouldn't

25:08.227 --> 25:09.961
lose even more blood,
but now that it's in,

25:09.995 --> 25:11.362
every minute puts you in more danger.

25:11.396 --> 25:12.530
- No.
- Gary...

25:12.564 --> 25:14.165
- Dr. Rhodes...
- Get away!

25:14.199 --> 25:17.535
Gary, listen to me.

25:17.569 --> 25:19.537
I do not want you to die.

25:19.571 --> 25:21.038
We have to get you to hospital.

25:21.073 --> 25:22.140
Do you understand?

25:22.174 --> 25:25.676
You are not taking my leg.

25:25.711 --> 25:27.845
I wish we didn't have to,

25:27.880 --> 25:29.514
but you've lost a lot of blood

25:29.548 --> 25:31.849
and you are in grave danger.

25:31.884 --> 25:34.485
[SNIFFLES] You can't.

25:34.520 --> 25:35.786
Please.

25:35.821 --> 25:37.388
There's gotta be another way.

25:37.422 --> 25:38.689
I'm sorry,

25:38.724 --> 25:40.625
there isn't.

25:40.659 --> 25:43.027
And I know how terrible this seems,

25:43.061 --> 25:45.029
but you have a lot of years to live

25:45.063 --> 25:47.131
and a lot of life to experience,

25:47.166 --> 25:49.446
and I don't want you
to miss out on that,

25:49.535 --> 25:50.735
but you will

25:50.798 --> 25:52.403
unless you let us help you

25:52.509 --> 25:53.759
right now.

25:53.872 --> 25:56.712
But it's my leg.

25:57.442 --> 25:58.676
I can't...

25:58.710 --> 26:01.212
<i>♪</i>

26:01.246 --> 26:02.747
You can.

26:02.781 --> 26:05.316
<i>♪</i>

26:05.350 --> 26:07.318
Good.

26:07.352 --> 26:13.090
<i>♪</i>

26:13.125 --> 26:15.593
Now, Dr. Rhodes is going to numb you up.

26:15.627 --> 26:18.036
After that, you won't feel anything.

26:19.531 --> 26:21.693
Just keep looking at me, Gary.

26:21.800 --> 26:23.267
I've got you.

26:23.302 --> 26:30.374
<i>♪</i>

26:33.412 --> 26:36.380
[SAW BUZZING]

26:36.415 --> 26:39.750
[WHIMPERING]

26:39.785 --> 26:42.186
♪

26:42.221 --> 26:43.254
Gah!

26:46.797 --> 26:48.496
- [ALARM BEEPING]
- Dr. Manning.

26:50.046 --> 26:52.054
- What's happening?
- He's having a seizure.

26:52.234 --> 26:54.002
Give him a bolus of Ativan.

26:54.101 --> 26:56.075
O2 sats are down to 72.

26:56.106 --> 26:57.207
He can't get any air.

26:57.232 --> 26:59.005
Bolus is in.

26:59.401 --> 27:01.369
He could suffer an anoxic brain injury.

27:01.505 --> 27:04.238
Give him 0.1 milligrams of morphine.

27:04.273 --> 27:07.208
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

27:07.242 --> 27:10.378
[MACHINES BEEPING]

27:10.412 --> 27:12.380
[MONITOR BEEPING]

27:12.506 --> 27:13.973
Stats down to 67.

27:14.008 --> 27:17.410
He can't go much longer.
Give him another 0.1.

27:17.444 --> 27:21.481
<i>♪</i>

27:21.515 --> 27:25.552
[MACHINES CONTINUE BEEPING]

27:27.588 --> 27:29.322
[MONITOR BEEPING]

27:29.356 --> 27:31.558
Sats back to 77.

27:31.592 --> 27:33.359
81.

27:33.394 --> 27:34.661
He's breathing.

27:34.695 --> 27:36.380
Get a pediatric intubation kit.

27:36.419 --> 27:37.397
Is this happens again, we're going to

27:37.431 --> 27:39.499
have to put him on a vent.

27:39.533 --> 27:45.672
<i>♪</i>

27:46.440 --> 27:48.007
Right.

27:48.042 --> 27:51.578
You have a very expressive face.

27:51.612 --> 27:53.079
Easy to read.

27:53.113 --> 27:57.083
I'm not sure that's a good thing.

27:57.117 --> 28:00.755
When I told Bert
that I was terminally ill,

28:01.185 --> 28:04.614
my greatest fear was
that he would leave me.

28:05.392 --> 28:08.194
We had only been dating
a couple of months.

28:08.229 --> 28:11.064
[COUGHS]

28:15.069 --> 28:18.204
But he didn't. He stuck with me

28:18.239 --> 28:20.139
through thick and thin.

28:20.174 --> 28:23.476
He doesn't deserve
to have me leave him now.

28:23.510 --> 28:26.045
So if you need to take extreme measures

28:26.080 --> 28:28.081
to keep me alive,

28:28.115 --> 28:32.552
do it.

28:32.586 --> 28:35.255
Are you sure?

28:35.289 --> 28:36.923
Yes.

28:36.957 --> 28:38.491
And you understand that means

28:38.525 --> 28:41.461
I may need to intubate you very soon?

28:41.495 --> 28:43.129
I promise,

28:43.163 --> 28:46.299
this is my decision... [GASPS]

28:46.333 --> 28:48.134
Not his.

28:48.168 --> 28:50.136
[COUGHS]

28:50.170 --> 28:52.739
Okay.

28:52.773 --> 28:55.775
I'll go change the order.

28:57.378 --> 29:00.246
[COUGHS]

29:01.282 --> 29:03.416
And he's gonna die.

29:03.450 --> 29:06.286
He could, yeah.

29:06.320 --> 29:07.654
And you... you really think

29:07.688 --> 29:09.589
that having me hold him is gonna help?

29:09.623 --> 29:11.090
I know it's a lot to ask,

29:11.125 --> 29:12.759
and I-I just wouldn't be doing it

29:12.793 --> 29:15.828
if the situation wasn't so dire,

29:15.863 --> 29:18.264
but you're his mother,
and... and the baby needs you,

29:18.299 --> 29:19.966
and I... if there's any chance at all

29:20.000 --> 29:23.436
that your holding him might
help him get better,

29:23.470 --> 29:26.706
I think we should try.

29:26.740 --> 29:29.309
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

29:29.343 --> 29:31.611
This was my... my fault.

29:31.645 --> 29:35.114
<i>♪</i>

29:35.149 --> 29:37.450
I did this to him.

29:37.484 --> 29:44.691
<i>♪</i>

29:46.160 --> 29:49.062
Okay.

29:49.096 --> 29:51.164
Okay.

29:52.833 --> 29:55.802
[BABY CRYING]

29:55.836 --> 30:03.042
<i>♪</i>

30:09.550 --> 30:11.651
He's so small.

30:11.685 --> 30:13.419
Go ahead.

30:13.454 --> 30:20.693
<i>♪</i>

30:23.697 --> 30:25.732
Hold him close, now.

30:25.766 --> 30:27.834
Against your skin.

30:27.868 --> 30:29.902
[BABY QUIETS]

30:29.937 --> 30:32.705
Hi. Don't cry.

30:32.740 --> 30:35.174
[LAUGHS]

30:35.209 --> 30:42.248
<i>♪</i>

30:47.755 --> 30:51.858
Hi. Hi, yeah?

30:51.892 --> 30:53.559
- [LABORED BREATHING]
- Dr. Halstead?

30:53.594 --> 30:56.863
[ALARMS BEEPING]

30:57.765 --> 30:59.365
She's in SVT. 20 of etomidate,

30:59.400 --> 31:01.034
50 of cisatracurium.

31:01.068 --> 31:02.702
Grab the intubation kit
and charge the paddles to 25.

31:02.736 --> 31:04.137
What's happening?

31:04.171 --> 31:05.805
The infection's overwhelming her system.

31:05.839 --> 31:07.373
She rescinded her DNR, so I have to

31:07.408 --> 31:09.542
shock her heart back
into rhythm and intubate.

31:09.576 --> 31:11.411
Mr. Goodwin, I need you to step back.

31:11.445 --> 31:14.981
She's doing this for me, isn't she?

31:15.015 --> 31:17.450
She... she doesn't want this. Stop.

31:17.484 --> 31:19.552
Stop.

31:19.586 --> 31:20.820
Lyla.

31:20.854 --> 31:22.588
Lyla, this is a shockable rhythm.

31:22.623 --> 31:24.924
I can try to resuscitate you.
Do you want me to do that?

31:24.958 --> 31:29.128
[LABORED BREATHING]

31:29.163 --> 31:30.129
No.

31:30.164 --> 31:31.664
You heard her. You heard her.

31:31.698 --> 31:32.899
Don't do this.

31:32.933 --> 31:34.834
[SNIFFLES] Don't...

31:34.868 --> 31:37.570
[LABORED BREATHING]

31:37.604 --> 31:42.742
<i>♪</i>

31:42.776 --> 31:44.911
[CRIES]

31:44.945 --> 31:46.312
I love you.

31:46.346 --> 31:48.414
<i>♪</i>

31:48.449 --> 31:50.450
I love you.

31:50.484 --> 31:57.557
<i>♪</i>

32:01.662 --> 32:04.630
[MACHINE FLAT-LINES]

32:04.665 --> 32:09.602
<i>♪</i>

32:09.636 --> 32:11.971
[CRIES]

32:12.005 --> 32:19.278
<i>♪</i>

32:28.055 --> 32:31.457
[SIREN BEEPING]

32:31.492 --> 32:32.658
Baghdad.

32:32.693 --> 32:33.793
All right, Karen,

32:33.827 --> 32:34.894
tell the OR we're on our way up

32:34.928 --> 32:36.229
as soon as this rebar's out.

32:36.263 --> 32:37.797
100 milligrams of ketamine.

32:37.831 --> 32:39.398
Get me a cut-down kit.

32:39.433 --> 32:42.335
And hang two units of
O neg on the rapid transfuser.

32:42.369 --> 32:45.338
<i>[TENSE MUSIC]</i>

32:45.372 --> 32:46.706
On my count.

32:46.740 --> 32:49.809
One, two, three.

32:49.843 --> 32:51.577
All right. Thanks, guys.

32:51.612 --> 32:57.850
<i>♪</i>

32:57.885 --> 32:59.485
Is that a REBOA?

32:59.520 --> 33:01.154
Couldn't get it down in the ambo.

33:01.188 --> 33:03.055
Pressure tanked every time I tried.

33:03.090 --> 33:04.724
Of course it does. A REBOA in the field

33:04.758 --> 33:05.992
is a problem waiting to happen.

33:06.026 --> 33:08.327
- Whose idea was this?
- Mine.

33:08.362 --> 33:10.329
- Dr. Rhodes, do you realize...
- It was the right call.

33:10.364 --> 33:12.899
There was no other way
to get him out of there alive.

33:12.933 --> 33:15.234
<i>♪</i>

33:15.269 --> 33:16.836
All right, wound looks good.

33:16.870 --> 33:17.837
Taking down the REBOA.

33:17.871 --> 33:21.073
Watch the pressure.

33:21.108 --> 33:23.109
Pressure's holding.

33:23.143 --> 33:24.744
Vitals are stable.

33:24.778 --> 33:25.778
All right, let's get this thing out

33:25.812 --> 33:27.380
and get him up to the OR.

33:27.414 --> 33:29.015
Ready?

33:29.049 --> 33:31.951
- Yep.
- One, two, three.

33:31.985 --> 33:33.719
<i>♪</i>

33:33.754 --> 33:35.721
[WINCES]

33:35.756 --> 33:39.759
<i>♪</i>

33:39.793 --> 33:43.529
No bleeding. Let's go.

33:43.564 --> 33:44.697
Nice job, Dr. Rhodes.

33:44.731 --> 33:51.938
<i>♪</i>

33:53.240 --> 33:55.708
[DISTANT SIREN WAILING]

33:55.742 --> 34:03.015
<i>♪</i>

34:04.785 --> 34:07.920
- Yes, that's it.
- Right there.

34:08.989 --> 34:11.924
Oh, excuse me.

34:11.958 --> 34:13.159
Can I just have a quick word

34:13.193 --> 34:14.627
with... with Ms. Crawford first?

34:14.661 --> 34:16.929
Okay.

34:18.864 --> 34:21.100
Hey.

34:22.335 --> 34:24.237
Oh, wow, he looks great.

34:24.271 --> 34:26.505
A lot better, huh?

34:26.540 --> 34:27.907
He is great.

34:27.940 --> 34:29.275
So, um,

34:29.309 --> 34:31.077
we have finally made some room for him

34:31.110 --> 34:32.777
in the intensive care unit,

34:32.813 --> 34:35.414
so we're gonna... we're gonna
take him up there now.

34:35.449 --> 34:36.815
Okay.

34:36.850 --> 34:38.317
Oh, do I carry him up,

34:38.351 --> 34:42.487
or do we take him up in the warmer?

34:42.522 --> 34:44.257
Well, um...

34:44.291 --> 34:45.690
Actually, LeAnn, there is a...

34:45.726 --> 34:48.761
there's a... there's
a foster couple up there

34:48.795 --> 34:52.498
who is gonna be looking
after him from here on out.

34:52.532 --> 34:57.336
<i>♪</i>

34:57.371 --> 34:59.105
But he likes me so much.

34:59.139 --> 35:00.139
I know.

35:00.173 --> 35:03.609
And he is doing so well.

35:03.644 --> 35:05.044
So... so I should

35:05.078 --> 35:06.612
just keep holding him.

35:06.647 --> 35:08.447
I really wish you could.

35:08.482 --> 35:09.715
Really, I do.

35:09.750 --> 35:11.651
But you said that he needs me.

35:11.685 --> 35:14.353
I know. I know I did.

35:14.388 --> 35:17.690
I know how difficult this is.
I really do.

35:17.724 --> 35:20.793
I'm sorry, but
we need to take the baby now.

35:20.819 --> 35:23.018
No!

35:24.097 --> 35:26.032
I'm his mother!

35:26.066 --> 35:28.167
I'm... I'm his mother.

35:28.201 --> 35:30.136
Doctor... Dr. Charles, please...

35:30.170 --> 35:31.671
- I'm sorry.
- You know.

35:31.705 --> 35:32.872
You know. Dr. Charles,

35:32.906 --> 35:34.240
please, can you help me? Please!

35:34.274 --> 35:35.474
- I'm sorry.
- Please, can you help me?

35:35.509 --> 35:37.576
Please explain. That is my baby.

35:37.611 --> 35:39.312
Dr. Charles, please.

35:39.346 --> 35:42.581
Please, can you just...
Dr. Charles, can you please...

35:42.616 --> 35:44.016
<i>♪</i>

35:46.875 --> 35:48.906
I saw Bert.

35:49.176 --> 35:50.682
He's taking it pretty hard.

35:50.729 --> 35:54.533
Yeah, I'm gonna send the kids
over to check on him.

35:54.580 --> 35:56.010
Mm.

35:56.750 --> 35:58.384
What?

35:58.419 --> 36:01.448
Sharon, do you think people can change?

36:01.855 --> 36:05.525
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

36:05.683 --> 36:07.956
Maggie, I don't know.

36:09.363 --> 36:11.532
Go call my kids.

36:18.372 --> 36:19.869
LeAnn...

36:19.986 --> 36:23.016
you lost a lot of blood today.
I'd really rather you stay.

36:23.066 --> 36:25.267
Listen, it may not feel like it,

36:25.326 --> 36:26.593
but you did the right thing today.

36:26.636 --> 36:28.237
You were there for your baby.

36:28.271 --> 36:30.906
It's unfortunate
that you can't take him home,

36:30.940 --> 36:33.142
but there's a methadone clinic
right upstairs.

36:33.176 --> 36:34.476
We can help you get cleaned up,

36:34.511 --> 36:35.778
and if you can get back on your feet,

36:35.812 --> 36:37.579
that's the crucial first step

36:37.614 --> 36:38.914
in getting him back.

36:38.948 --> 36:41.517
I'm tired.

36:41.551 --> 36:42.951
You know, I'm...

36:43.288 --> 36:46.046
I'm just gonna go.

36:46.556 --> 36:47.944
LeAnn...

36:48.124 --> 36:49.591
LeAnn.

36:49.626 --> 36:52.594
<i>[SOMBER MUSIC]</i>

36:52.629 --> 36:54.163
We had no choice. We had to do

36:54.197 --> 36:56.833
- what's right for the baby.
- Oh, yeah, of course.

36:57.066 --> 36:58.834
It's just, you know...

36:58.868 --> 37:01.804
It's sad.
It's unlikely either of them...

37:01.838 --> 37:04.606
ever really be whole again.

37:04.641 --> 37:07.609
[SIGHS]

37:07.644 --> 37:11.547
<i>♪</i>

37:11.581 --> 37:15.617
Ah, the old Chapman flow charts.

37:15.652 --> 37:17.286
Oh, yeah.

37:17.320 --> 37:19.822
Number seven. That there's a doozy.

37:19.856 --> 37:22.457
Step seven?

37:24.861 --> 37:27.729
Dr. Reese, the truth is,

37:27.764 --> 37:31.033
I feel responsible
for letting your situation get

37:31.067 --> 37:33.068
out of hand the way it did.

37:33.102 --> 37:36.305
It was my job to, well, guide you

37:36.339 --> 37:39.727
and teach you and make you
a better doctor, and I...

37:39.909 --> 37:40.976
I let you down.

37:41.010 --> 37:43.178
- Dr. Charles...
- But ultimately,

37:43.213 --> 37:46.511
some relationships are just better...

37:47.654 --> 37:49.155
kept intact,

37:49.252 --> 37:51.486
which is why, if you'd still like to,

37:51.521 --> 37:52.988
when you return,

37:53.022 --> 37:55.858
I would very much
welcome back on my service.

37:57.694 --> 38:00.329
Really?

38:00.363 --> 38:02.030
Really.

38:09.639 --> 38:11.874
Hey, Gary.

38:14.410 --> 38:17.880
How you doing?

38:17.914 --> 38:20.382
It's weird.

38:20.416 --> 38:22.017
I can feel it,

38:22.051 --> 38:23.518
like it's still there.

38:23.553 --> 38:26.455
Yeah, it's called phantom limb pain.

38:26.489 --> 38:27.856
Uh...

38:27.891 --> 38:31.326
takes some time, but it will fade.

38:34.564 --> 38:37.099
Listen, Gary, I am...

38:37.133 --> 38:40.469
I am very sorry about your leg.

38:40.503 --> 38:42.738
[SCOFFS]

38:42.772 --> 38:45.908
At least I'm still alive.

38:48.578 --> 38:50.879
I'll find a way to move on.

38:50.914 --> 38:54.082
<i>[SOLEMN MUSIC]</i>

38:54.117 --> 38:55.817
All right, bud.

38:55.852 --> 38:58.553
I'll check on you soon.

38:58.588 --> 39:05.594
<i>♪</i>

39:07.697 --> 39:10.599
Dr. Charles.

39:10.633 --> 39:13.602
I didn't want to believe
that it was over,

39:13.636 --> 39:16.805
but you were right.
I need to let Robin go.

39:16.839 --> 39:24.112
<i>♪</i>

39:33.790 --> 39:35.257
April?

39:35.291 --> 39:37.526
Hmm?

39:37.560 --> 39:39.094
Who's that?

39:39.128 --> 39:41.530
<i>♪</i>

39:41.564 --> 39:42.831
It's my sister.

39:42.865 --> 39:44.766
What?

39:44.801 --> 39:47.002
Emily.

39:47.036 --> 39:49.304
I should've told you.

39:49.339 --> 39:52.975
I never talk about her. It's painful.

39:53.009 --> 39:56.778
My parents adopted Emily
when she was four.

39:56.813 --> 39:59.982
She had a hard life
before she even came to us.

40:00.016 --> 40:01.283
Still does.

40:01.317 --> 40:04.119
She makes bad decisions, acts out,

40:04.153 --> 40:05.620
then blows up when I try to help her,

40:05.655 --> 40:07.055
and I swore the last time
that I wouldn't

40:07.090 --> 40:08.957
let myself get involved again.

40:08.992 --> 40:11.960
When was that?

40:11.995 --> 40:14.463
It was four years ago.

40:14.497 --> 40:19.801
<i>♪</i>

40:19.836 --> 40:22.037
Maybe I should give her a call.

40:22.071 --> 40:26.675
<i>♪</i>

40:26.709 --> 40:28.210
Hey.

40:28.244 --> 40:31.713
Thank you for today. Uh, you were great.

40:31.748 --> 40:35.684
I did feel a bit like
Bonnie Henna out there.

40:35.718 --> 40:36.985
Who?

40:37.020 --> 40:39.821
South African action hero.

40:39.856 --> 40:41.089
Have a good night.

40:41.124 --> 40:42.924
Oh, and no need to cover for me
tomorrow.

40:42.959 --> 40:44.326
I'll be here.

40:44.360 --> 40:45.861
You're not going to Minneapolis?

40:45.895 --> 40:47.696
Nope.

40:47.730 --> 40:54.803
<i>♪</i>

40:57.540 --> 41:00.208
Good evening, sir. Can I help you?

41:00.243 --> 41:02.711
I'm looking for a change.

41:02.745 --> 41:04.513
What model is this?

41:04.547 --> 41:05.847
The 911 4S.

41:05.882 --> 41:07.904
Beautiful car.

41:09.552 --> 41:11.520
Yes, it is.

41:11.821 --> 41:12.954
You got the keys?

41:12.989 --> 41:14.289
I'm sorry, but we're actually

41:14.323 --> 41:17.177
done doing test drives for the night.

41:17.293 --> 41:20.794
I don't want to test drive.
I want to buy it.

41:20.856 --> 41:24.395
Oh, of course. Just give me a moment.

41:24.567 --> 41:29.037
<i>♪</i>

41:29.072 --> 41:30.605
[ALARM BEEPS]

41:30.640 --> 41:32.941
Mm.

41:36.913 --> 41:39.629
- I'll see you in the morning.
- Mm.

41:40.083 --> 41:41.483
No.

41:41.508 --> 41:43.987
You should stay.

41:44.754 --> 41:46.955
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm.

41:46.989 --> 41:48.557
What about Owen?

41:48.591 --> 41:50.058
Mm.

41:50.093 --> 41:52.594
He's got to find out sometime.

41:52.628 --> 41:53.895
Are you sure?

41:53.930 --> 41:56.403
Mm-hmm. I'm sure.

41:56.660 --> 42:00.262
This is so much better than
scraping ice off my windshield.

42:00.301 --> 42:01.903
[LAUGHS]

42:01.938 --> 42:08.276
<i>♪</i>

